<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911205-0042</DOCNO><DOCID>911205-0042.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Stop andamp; Shop Cos.:   Loss Posted for 3rd Period;   Operating Profit Increased</HL><DATE>12/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5</SO><CO>   SHP</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>MASSACHUSETTS (MA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Stop andamp; Shop Cos., Boston, reporting its first quarterlyfigures since a recent public stock offering, posted a smallnet loss for its third quarter, but an increase in operatingprofit.   For the third quarter ended Nov. 9, the company had a lossof $400,000, or one cent a share, compared with a loss of$6.7 million or 20 cents a share, in the year-earlier period.</LP><TEXT>   Operating profit in the quarter increased 31% to $40.2million on a 2% increase in sales to $1.12 billion from $1.1billion. Debt-service payments of $38 million in the quarterby the highly leveraged company and other costs resulted inthe net loss.   The company, which was taken private in a $1.2 billionleveraged buy-out by Kohlberg, Kravis, Roberts andamp; Co. in 1988,raised $212.5 million in an initial public offering completedin late November; proceeds were earmarked to reduce thecompany's $1.28 billion in long-term debt. KKR's partnershipsstill own a 59% stake in the company.   Some of the largest operating gains came from the130-store Bradlees Discount Department Stores. The remainderof the company's sales come from 118 Stop andamp; ShopSupermarkets.</TEXT></DOC>